1781096852039465	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4RI		item.create	bn-6xpz	{"description":"Found dogfooding the bn-21cj fix (debug build post-fc0dd397, /tmp fake repo).\nbn-21cj fixed the REPLAY path: after replaying commits, the summary verifies the\nfinal HEAD via workspace::conflict_state and reports residual committed conflicts\ninstead of \"replayed cleanly\". But the NO-OP path was not touched: when a workspace\nis already at the current epoch (e.g. a quiet sibling auto-rebase just committed a\nstructured conflict into it and synced its refs), `maw ws sync <ws>` prints only\n\"Workspace '<ws>' is up to date.\" — no mention that the workspace has 1 unresolved\ncommitted conflict, while `ws resolve --list`, `ws list` (lifecycle:conflicted), and\nthe merge gate all report it. Repro: two workspaces edit the same line; merge one\n(sibling auto-rebases with conflict); then `maw ws sync <sibling>` -> \"up to date\",\nsilent about the conflict. The up-to-date/fast-forward summary should consult the\nsame effective_conflict_state helper and append e.g. \"but has 1 unresolved\nconflict(s): maw ws resolve <ws> --list\".\nRelated cleanup in the same message block: the conflict guidance printed by sync\nstill ends with \"After resolving, commit and clear conflict state: ... maw ws sync\n<ws>\" — since bn-8zqz any reader auto-clears stale sidecars, so the trailing sync\nstep is no longer required; reword to avoid re-teaching the old two-step dance.\n","kind":"bug","title":"maw ws sync no-op path stays silent about residual committed conflicts"}	blake3:qAlb6D_NEdwpvdKTChkBu3Tgzci0LuD23avkRmH1uFY
1781096852350813	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4hI		item.create	bn-1olb	{"description":"Found dogfooding bn-1abp(3b) (debug build post-5c3f726c, /tmp fake repo). The new\ndefault base for `maw ws diff <ws>` is the CURRENT epoch (fixed the lagging\ndefault-ws-state-ref misattribution). But for a workspace that is BEHIND the epoch\n(stale, e.g. after a merge ran with --no-auto-rebase), diffing worktree-vs-current-\nepoch shows the epoch's own advance inverted as phantom workspace edits: a file\nanother workspace merged after this workspace's base shows up as \"deleted\" in the\ndiff even though this workspace never touched it. Repro: ws dave commits a 1-line\nedit; merge ws erin (new file erin.txt) with --no-auto-rebase; `maw ws diff dave`\n-> \"erin.txt deleted\" + dave's edit. After `maw ws sync dave` the diff is correct.\nExpected: a stale workspace should diff against its OWN base epoch (the workspace\nepoch ref the staleness machinery already tracks), or the merge-base of HEAD and\nthe current epoch — \"what THIS workspace changed\", never the epoch delta inverted.\nAt minimum print a loud warning when the workspace base != current epoch.\n","kind":"bug","title":"maw ws diff on a STALE workspace misattributes the epoch's own advance as workspace changes"}	blake3:TtltdtEAvFZiIK2cNfojBAIamKpHExc9x8APoUaE4ok
1781096852677084	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy4xI		item.create	bn-1nwn	{"description":"Pre-existing behavior made glaring by bn-36zz hunk-level rendering (debug build\npost-feb7b2dc, /tmp fake repo). The structured resolve path materializes `--keep\n<side>` by writing the chosen side's WHOLE blob from the sidecar OIDs. With\nhunk-level rendering the conflicted file now correctly preserves the other side's\nnon-conflicting edits as cleanly-merged body content — but `--keep <side>` then\nthrows those away silently. Repro: ws iris edits line A (conflicts with merged ws\nhenry) and line B (no overlap); after henry merges, iris's rendered file shows one\nconflict hunk at A and her clean B edit merged in the body; `maw ws resolve iris\n--keep epoch` -> file is epoch's whole blob: iris's B edit is silently reverted\n(recoverable only from git history). Violates least surprise and the spirit of\nno-work-lost: the rendered file says \"your B edit merged cleanly\", the resolver\nthen deletes it. Expected: --keep <side> should resolve PER CONFLICT HUNK — re-run\nthe 3-way text merge with that side winning conflicts (the gix builtin text driver\nmaw-git already wraps supports ResolveWith::Ours/Theirs; merge_text_with_style) so\ncleanly-merged regions survive. --keep both has the same whole-side semantics and\nshould get the same treatment (Union style). If whole-side replacement is ever the\nintent, it needs a different flag name and an explicit warning listing the edits\nbeing dropped.\n","kind":"bug","title":"maw ws resolve --keep <side> discards the other side's cleanly-merged edits (whole-side blob materialization)"}	blake3:2-VlzpW1Or6OlXjWSMNM4c2i0MAFYLRiTTBqY2g3jK4
